    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-12-04T20:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-12-04T20:00:00-05:00" n="377"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d377">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 103.96/1681f</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Chargé in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LIB1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Laughlin</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-12-04T20:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 4, 1918, 8 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3225. For <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SLP1">Sheldon</persName> [from
                    War Trade Board]:</p>
                <p>No. 1774. We have advised the British Embassy here that we would participate in
                    the purchase price of some 245 tons of molybdenum <pb facs="0460" n="1294"
                        xml:id="pg_1294"/> from Norway, which has already been the subject of some
                    correspondence between us, in the following manner: That any recovery due to the
                    United States on account of its share in the purchase of the 2,000,000 tons of
                    Swedish iron ore, provided for in the agreement of May 29, 1918, may be used to
                    pay our moiety of the purchase price of the molybdenum. We have also advised the
                    French that we would participate to the extent of one-third in the French and
                    British purchase of 41,000 tons of low phosphorous iron ore from Sweden in the
                    same manner. The Executive order of June 29, 1918, providing for our
                    participation in the purchase of the 2,000,000 tons of Swedish iron ore, has
                    been amended so as to make possible our participation in the molybdenum purchase
                    and the low phosphorous iron ore purchased in the manner indicated.</p>
                <p>We are sending to you by pouch forthwith amended form of said Executive order and
                    letters to the British and French Embassies,<note n="1" xml:id="d377fn1">Not
                        printed.</note> which will furnish you with greater details.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PFL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Polk</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
